# Prefer events/queues over timers

Do **not** reach for `QTimer` (or sleep-based delays) to coalesce bursts, defer UI work, or “debounce” core listener storms when the Qt event queue can do the same job.

## Prefer

- A **pending flag** plus one `QMetaObject::invokeMethod(..., Qt::QueuedConnection)` (or a dedicated signal with `Qt::QueuedConnection`) so many arrivals collapse into a single later slot.
- Existing queues already drained by a flush slot (batch lists, pending maps) when the work is naturally batchable.
- Immediate, targeted updates when the event carries enough identity (e.g. a TTH) and the model can update one row cheaply.

## Avoid

- Single-shot timers whose only purpose is “wait a bit then refresh everything.”
- Artificial intervals that hide races instead of ordering work on the event loop.

## When a timer is appropriate

Use a timer only when the delay itself is part of the product behavior (progress ticks, search countdown, periodic status, user-visible timeouts)—not as a substitute for coalescing queued work.
